reviewText: Not for the beginner. But a great workout to help you break out of a plateau, also, there are so many ways to modify the difficulty for the less advanced, yet increase it for the advanced and even really ramp it up for the elite trainer. It would be hard to imagine anyone could finish this in its totality and not feel like they climbed a mountain. Good luck with this and GO FOR IT!

reviewText: The workout on this DVD is top notch, but there are no chapter cues that allow you to customize if you don't have 72 minutes.Here's a breakdown of where each section starts and approximately how long each section is:Warm-up: 1:00 (5 min.)Block 1: 6:00 (10 min.)Block 2: 16:00 (11 min.)Block 3: 26:30 (12 min.)Block 4: 37:50 (12 min.)Block 5: 49:30 (11 min.)Block 6: 60:30 (6 min.)--BonusCool-Down: 66:00 (6 min.)With this information and the other 5-star review that gives you a breakdown of the actual exercises, you have all you need to purchase this DVD with confidence.Enjoy!

reviewText: I consider myself at an intermediate level of fitness.Pros:  Tough workout.  Overall, like the moves.  Camera work and music is fine.  Backup people are non-annoying.Cons:  Instructor is not my favorite.  A little too happy/giggly for me and gets kind of screechy when the going gets tough (understandable but not pleasant to listen to.)  Also, he was having quite a lot of technical difficulties with his mike pack.  Should really have re-done the shots instead of immortalizing him fiddling, removing, and readjusting throughout.  Also, the volume was all over the place --- could barely hear sometimes and then way too loud.  Most of my cons would be solved with a music only option (which I think every workout DVD should have.)  Instead they offer a no music option --- almost pointless really since it is easier to mute and play your own music.Overall, a good enough workout to keep but will probably go with the TV on mute.

reviewText: This is the first workout I've bought by Paul Katami so I wasn't sure what to expect with his personality, but I had read good reviews of this DVD on a fitness forum, so I decided to give it a try.  I really like this workout!  Paul is very motivating and encouraging, and he makes it possible to get through this hard workout while enjoying it.The set is very plain and minimal, and there are two female background exercises.  Paul also works along with the workout.  (It's fun to see that he also struggles with how hard this workout is -- at one point, he sort of stumbles during a tough lunge sequence.)  They use just one pair of dumbbells, but I've found that I use three different sets of dumbbells.The workout follows this format:  one minute of aerobics, one minute of leg work, one minute of upper-body work, and one minute of abs/core. (The four-minute format is the reason for the "4x4" in the title of this workout.) There are five of these 4x4 blocks, and you repeat each of the five blocks twice, with a bonus segment at the very end of the workout.  It comes in at 60 minutes long.The only real negative is that the music on this workout is really bland and hard to hear.  While Paul's personality is engaging and enough to keep you motivated, it would be really nice to have some better music to help you stay pumped.  Overall, though, it's a great workout, and it's really tough!  I like it so much that I'm going to purchase a few more workouts from Paul.

reviewText: Hollywood Bootcamp 4x4 is an advanced and long workout, clocking in at about 1 hour, 11 minutes.  I did the low impact version and I had to simplify a few of the exercises.  If you go full blast with high impact jumps and fast movements, you need water and a towel for the sweat dripping down your face.  A pair of light, moderate, or medium weight dumbbells are also needed. Paul Katami works with two ladies.The "4" simply refers to the pattern of the workout in which you focus on 4 areas.  Here are the 4 areas of target.1. Cardio2. Lower body3. Upper body4. CoreHere is the workout breakdown.
